overview: "In computing , a cache ( /k√¶?/ ( listen ) kash , [1] or /'ke??/ kaysh in AuE[2] ) is a hardware or software  component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored  in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere. A cache hit occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a cache miss occurs when it  cannot. Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a  result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache,  the faster the system performs." (Wikipedia)
title: MUCUS (uncacheable)
